The '''''Nivôse''''' is a light surveillance frigate ("''frégate de surveillance''") of the French ''[[French Navy|Marine Nationale]]''. She is the third ship of the {{sclass-|Floréal|frigate|4}}, and the fourth French vessel named after the 4th month of the [[French Republican Calendar|Republican Calendar]].
== Deployments == * 2001 In October 2001, she was deployed in the Persian Gulf as part of [[Operation Enduring Freedom|Operation ''Enduring Freedom'']].<ref>[http://www.netmarine.net/bat/fregates/nivose/actu.htm Histoire et actualités de la frégate ''Nivôse''], netmarine.net</ref> *2008 In late 2008, under [[frigate captain]] Jean-Marc Le Quilliec,<ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/international/article/2008/12/02/alerte-aux-pirates-a-bord-du-nivose_1125786_3210.html Piraterie : une nuit d'alerte sur le ''Nivôse''], ''[[Le Monde]]'', 2 December 2008</ref> ''Nivôse'' was deployed as part of a [[European Union]] expeditionary force, [[Operation Atalanta|Operation ''Atalanta'']], in the [[Gulf of Aden]] to fight [[Piracy in Somalia|piracy off Somalia]].<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/12/04/yemen.pirates/index.html?iref=topnews Suspected pirates rescued in Gulf of Aden], [[CNN]], 5 December 2008</ref> *2009 On 15 April 2009, she captured eleven pirates {{convert|900|km|mi|abbr=on}} East of [[Mombasa]], and thwarted an attack on the Liberian-registered merchantman ''[[Safmarine Asia]]''.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8000447.stm], [[BBC News]], 15 April 2009</ref><ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/africa/04/15/somalia.pirates/index.html French capture 11 suspected pirates; Greek ship freed], CNN</ref>
On 12 April 2009, ''Nivôse'' relieved her sister-ship ''Floréal'' as part of [[European Union Naval Force Somalia – Operation ATALANTA]]. On 3 May 2009, 900&nbsp;km off Somalia, the crew managed to lure pirates to attack the ship by sailing into the sun to avoid being identified and mistaken for a merchantman; as the pirate closed in, she turned about and launched her on-boarded helicopter and fast outboard vessels. Eleven pirates were captured.<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/africa/05/03/kenya.pirates Pirates seized after threatening French navy ship], CNN, 3 May 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/afrique/article/2009/05/03/somalie-la-marine-francaise-capture-onze-pirates_1188254_3212.html Somalie : la marine française capture onze pirates], Lemonde.fr</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8031701.stm Somali pirate suspects captured], BBC, 3 May 2009</ref> *2010 From 5 to 7 March 2010, joining mission forces from France, Italy, Luxembourg, Spain and Sweden, ''Nivôse'' secured its "biggest seizure" so far in the vital shipping lane, with 35 pirates arrested and four mother ships seized in three days off Somalia.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=87&art_id=nw20100309020612247C690576 |title= European naval forces capture more pirates |accessdate= 9 Mar 2010 |date= 9 Mar 2010 |publisher= [[Independent Online (South Africa)]] |quote= Six pirate action groups have been intercepted, mother ships and skiffs have been destroyed and over 40 pirates have been taken into custody }}</ref>
==Fire== *On 30 September 2014, ''Nivôse'' was severely damaged by fire which broke out in her engine room. {{ship|French frigate|Floréal|F730|2}} assisted in firefighting operations. ''Nivôse'' was subsequently towed in to ''Port de la Pointe des Galets''.<ref name=Fire>{{cite web |url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/138784/french-frigate-extensively-damaged-by-violent-fire/ |title=French Frigate Extensively Damaged by Violent Fire |publisher=World Maritime News |accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>
